node.text:
Some of my go-tos! Enjoy 😊 

Greek Inspired Salad Jar
* 1-2 cups kale
* 1 tbsp feta cheese
* 4oz chicken thighs 
* 10 olives 
* ¼ cup red onion 
* ½ orange bell pepper 
* ½ cup chickpeas
* 1 tbsp balsamic

BLT Remix Salad jar 
* 1 cup mixed greens
* 2 pieces nitrate free bacon
* 2 eggs 
* ½ cup cucumber 
* 1 cup tomatoes 
* 2 tbsp paleo ranch

Veggie Goddess
* 1 cup mixed greens
* ½ cup red onion 
* ½ cup black beans 
* ½ cup quinoa
* ½ cup cucumber 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Tex Mex Jar Combo 
* 1 tbsp cilantro 
* 2 cup lettuce   
* 4oz ground turkey or grass-fed ground beef
* ½ cup corn
* ¼ cup onion 
* ½ cup bell peppers 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Coconut oil pulling benefits:
Fights bad breath,
improves gum health &
maintains teeth whitness.

What to do:
Step 1: Swish 1 tbsp coconut oil in your mouth for 10-15 min (yes min!) Step 2: Spit in trash afterwards since oil will clog the drains
Step 3: Brush your teeth normally after and floss like you normally would.

Cheers to great oral health!
Xoxo
Amanda

4 ways to salad jar! 🥗 (*swipe to see the anatomy of a salad jar and details on each combo*)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Salad jars aren’t just super pretty they’re also super practical. Here’s the deal - the way you stack the ingredients from wettest to driest keeps it fresh and crisp all week (5 days after making it)! Then when you’re ready to eat it, you just shake it up and pour it on a plate.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You won’t only impress your friends with how Pinterest friendly your food is but you also enjoy your salads without the usual soggy taste you get when you make them in advance the regular way.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Info on each salad jar below:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Greek salad jar: balsamic, chickpeas, bell peppers, onion, olives, chicken, feta + kale⁠⁠
Tex mex salad jar: balsamic, tomatoes, bell pepper, onion, corn, ground turkey + mixed greens⁠⁠
BLT Remix salad jar: 1-2 tbsp @primalkitchenfoods paleo ranch, tomatoes, cucumbers, 2 eggs, 2 pieces nitrate-free bacon, mixed greens⁠⁠
Veggie goddess: 1 tbsp balsamic, tomatoes, cucumbers, quinoa, beans, onion + mixed greens ⁠⁠
What combo is your fav?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
P.S. If you’re looking for more meal prep friendly recipes, make sure to check out my new Master Your Health Ebook, link in bio!⁠⁠

node.text:
How to Build a Delicious Homemade Salad Dressing (Swipe to see some salad ideas to go with each dressing)⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠There are so many ways to get creative with building a healthy salad dressing at home! That’s why I thought I’d share some inspiration using common base ingredients, vinegars/citrus, herbs & more in case you’re looking for some inspiration! ⁠⁠
While there are definitely some healthier pre-made salad dressings out there, a lot of store-bought salad dressings contain unhealthy oils, additives, sugars, etc., making it a good choice to make your own at home when possible. Not only are homemade dressings delicious and easy to make, but they can be customized to your liking and saved for later so you don’t have to make a new batch for every meal.⁠⁠
Details on each dressing below:⁠⁠
What you need for each dressing (note: don’t forget to add desired seasoning like salt, pepper, garlic, etc)⁠⁠
What you need for the Yogurt Ranch:⁠⁠
(makes 1 cup)⁠⁠
-½ cup Greek yogurt⁠⁠
-1 tbsp ACV ⁠⁠
-1.5 tbsp chives, chopped ⁠⁠
-1 tsp honey  ⁠⁠
What you need for the Balsamic Vinaigrette:⁠⁠
(makes about 1 cup)⁠⁠
- 1 cup olive oil ⁠⁠
-¼ cup balsamic ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp basil, minced ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp dijon mustard⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Creamy Tomato:⁠⁠
(makes ¾ cup) ⁠⁠
-½ cup paleo mayo⁠⁠
-1 tbsp white wine vinegar ⁠⁠
-1 tsp parsley, minced ⁠⁠
-½ cup sun dried tomatoes ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Lemon Ginger Tahini:⁠⁠
(makes ½-¾ cup)⁠⁠
-½ cup tahini ⁠⁠
-2 tbsp lemon juice ⁠⁠
-1 tsp ginger, minced ⁠⁠
-2 tsp maple syrup⁠⁠
What to do:⁠⁠
1- If making the Creamy Tomato, combine all ingredients in a blender and blend until smooth (you may need to add 1-2 tbsps water to help with blending).⁠⁠
2- For the others, mix together all ingredients in a large bowl until well combined. ⁠⁠
3- Enjoy right away or save for later. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Which would you choose?⁠⁠
Xoxo,⁠⁠
Amanda ⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
Therapy changed my life ❤️⁠
⁠
It really did. First time therapy saved my life was when I had an eating disorder in high school. I remember my mom super being stressed out about how thin I was getting. I was definitely in full-denial at first.⁠
⁠
It wasn’t until my doctor said I would need professional help because I was at a dangerously low weight that things started to turn around. I was 97 pounds at my lowest (over 36 lbs lighter than I am now) and I remember contemplating putting dumbbells in my sweat shirt pockets so the doctor wouldn’t know my real weight. ⁠
⁠
That was my first introduction to therapy and I can’t be more thankful for it. Having the accountability and emotional support I needed to work through my eating disorder was priceless.⁠
⁠
Again in my late 20s. I knew something was up with the way I handled conflict in interpersonal relationships but I didn’t know just what to do about it.⁠
⁠
I was so timid to be honest in my relationships about how I truly felt. I was so lost in pleasing other people that I actually lost part of myself in the process. Out of touch with my own emotions and being pushed around by others wasn’t getting me the deep, meaningful relationships I craved.⁠
⁠
I also knew the way I handled conflict in avoidance or passive aggressive manner wasn’t going to lead to a positive place and I wanted to change that.⁠
⁠
Working through some of my conflict-avoidance, passive-aggressive & people-pleasing tendencies was much more difficult than I thought it would be but it was well worth it!⁠
⁠
So if there’s anything I want you to take away is that you can most definitely make impactful change in your life. Sometimes it’s just about asking for the right help 😘⁠
⁠
I’m still a work-in-process but I’m so thankful you’re here for the wild ride with me!⁠
⁠
Amanda⁠
⁠
#mentalhealth #therapy

Swipe for different gut-healing foods (and save this post!) 👉🏼⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁠⁠
When it comes to eating for gut health, there are different strategies to take, and there's no one-size-fits-all recommendation! You have to figure out what works for you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Great post by my friend @maxlugavere ⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
More in this post below:⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Soluble fiber absorbs water and forms a gel, and feeds the bacteria that live in your large intestine, collectively known as your gut microbiome. As a result, those bacteria churn out powerful metabolites including short-chain fatty acids like butyrate. This type of fiber may help improve symptoms in people with IBS.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Insoluble fiber doesn't absorb water, but instead acts as an abrasive broom, sweeping up your GI tract. This type of fiber is usually well tolerated but can cause or exacerbate symptoms for some sensitive people, including people with IBS.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Resistant starch is a form of carbohydrate that acts like a fiber, is resistant to digestion and instead feeds those microbes at the latter end of your GI tract. There are multiple types of resistant starch. One form is found in unripe bananas/mangos, and another can be created when you cook and cool a starch, like a potato or rice. This is why sushi rice is actually quite healthy—b/c it's cooked and cooled.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Probiotic foods contain live and active bacteria cultures. These are some of my favorites! These are pretty well tolerated except by people with histamine issues.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
Love you guys!⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁣⁠⁠
🥰 Amanda⁠⁠

The difference between sugar with some coffee, and coffee with some flavor! (Swipe to see some healthier coffee options) ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Now there’s nothing wrong with treating yourself to these drinks on occasion, but consuming them regularly can really add up.⁠⁠ ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
It’s important to be aware of how much sugar you’re consuming each day. While it’s totally okay to have some days with a higher sugar intake than others, your overall consumption plays a crucial role in your health. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Added sugars like those in most Starbucks coffee drinks can become highly addicting, leading your body to crave more. That’s why I recommend going for coffee with some flavor like honey, stevia, cacao, etc. on a more regular basis. Plus, they’re straight up delicious! ⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Here are the details of each healthier coffee choice:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Honey Almond Milk Cold Brew:⁠⁠⁠
-8-10 oz brewed coffee, cooled⁠⁠⁠
-¼ cup unsweetened almond milk⁠⁠⁠
-1 tsp raw honey⁠⁠⁠
-stevia to taste ⁠⁠(or honey or maple syrup)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Homemade Java Chip Frappuccino:⁠⁠
-8-10 oz brewed coffee, cooled ⁠⁠
-½ cup unsweetened almond milk ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp cacao powder ⁠⁠
-1 tbsp chocolate chips⁠⁠
-2-3 cups ice⁠⁠
-stevia to taste ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Starbucks Cold Brew with milk of choice ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Homemade Vanilla Latte:⁠⁠
-8-10 oz brewed coffee, cooled ⁠⁠
-1 cup unsweetened almond milk ⁠⁠
-1 tsp vanilla extract⁠⁠
-stevia to taste ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What you need for the Chocolate Almond Espresso:⁠⁠
-1 cup unsweetened almond milk⁠⁠
-1 packet of instant espresso powder or brewed espresso⁠⁠
-1 tbsp cacao powder or cocoa powder⁠⁠
-Stevia to taste⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What to do: ⁠⁠
1- In a blender, combine cooled coffee along with other ingredients ⁠⁠
2- Pour the drink into a tall cup along with ice (unless making the java chip) and enjoy! ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Which would you go for?!⁠⁠
Xx,⁠⁠
Amanda ⁠⁠
⁠⁠

Can you believe these vintage ads? (Swipe to see more details)⁠⁠
⁠⁠
While food advertising regulations have gotten slightly better, there are still a bunch of manipulative marketing tactics companies use.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
While I definitely understand a certain level of marketing is normal and needed to promote a brand, I really get frustrated when there is borderline false advertisement and misleading packaging that would lead customers to believe the product is healthier than it really is.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
That’s why I wanted to empower you with this information today! With advertisements being thrown your way more than ever, it’s important to become an informed consumer.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You'll soon find some brands do live up to their claims while other brands fall extremely short. So remember to always read the ingredients and trust your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
xx,⁠⁠
 Amanda⁠⁠

Are you a parent with picky toddlers? ⠀
@kids.eat.in.color is a must follow for practical information surrounding #momlife and feeding your children!⠀
~⁣⠀
Luckily, I wasn’t a picky eater as a kid but if you’re struggling with picky eater this graphic helps show great options for making sure they’re still getting the vitamins and minerals they need.⠀
~⁣⠀
Of course there are many different tactics to help encourage healthy eating and always remember you get to choose what’s on the menu as a parent. Some helpful tips from Jennifer below.⠀
・・・⠀
"Doing lots of veggie exposures and in fun ways, but kid still doesn't eat veggies." Another #foodbattles post for you!⁣⠀⠀
~⁣⠀⠀
Keep exposing veggies and serving lots of fruit in the meantime! You may have heard "fruit has sugar, so it needs to be limited." This is absolutely not true for children. Please don't limit unless there are digestive issues or medical reasons. Fruit is loaded with all the vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, and fiber.⁣⠀⠀
~⁣⠀⠀
NOTE: Fruit juice is not a whole fruit. I recommend serving water as normal beverages and serving juice occasionally.⠀
~⁣⠀

Weight loss vs. muscle gain meal ideas! 💪 *Swipe to see lunch, dinner & snack idea*⁠⁠
⁠⁠
While no one meal will make you gain or lose weight, your meals and snacks for the day all together will add up to hit your target goals.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
As I always say, there is no one right way to eat. However, small things like portion size and type of food can make a big difference when you have a specific goal in mind like weight loss or muscle gain. For example, simply going for 2 tbsps of almond butter rather than 2 tbsps of Greek yogurt on a rice cake can add an extra 170 calories to your snack. A similar example would be going for cauliflower rice which is lower in calories than something like brown rice. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
There are so many simple adjustments like this that can really add up when it comes to getting the results you want with healthy eating. That’s why I wanted to share a few examples of how these simple changes can add up to big results. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Details on the differences of each below:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Breakfast:⁠⁠
-2 eggs -> 2 eggs + egg whites⁠⁠
-½ cup potatoes -> ¾ cup potatoes ⁠⁠
-2 slices bacon -> 3 slices bacon⁠⁠
-½ cup raspberries ⁠⁠
-1 cup spinach⁠⁠
- 1 tsp olive oil -> 2 tsp olive oil ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Lunch:⁠⁠
-2 cups mixed greens⁠⁠
-4 oz grilled chicken breast ⁠⁠
-1 cup tomatoes ⁠⁠
-1 cup cucumber ⁠⁠
-1 red bell pepper ⁠⁠
-½ cup sweet potato -> 1 cup ⁠⁠
-¼ cup quinoa -> ½ cup ⁠⁠
-¼ of an avocado -> ½ an avocado ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Snack:⁠⁠
-Brown rice cake⁠⁠
-2 tbsp Greek yogurt -> 2 ½ tbsp almond butter ⁠⁠
-2 strawberries -> none ⁠⁠
-½ a medium banana ⁠⁠
-½ tbsp chocolate chips ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Dinner: ⁠⁠
-4 oz wild caught salmon -> 5oz salmon⁠⁠
-½ cup cauliflower rice -> ¾ cup brown rice ⁠⁠
-1 cup mushrooms -> ⅓ cup mushrooms ⁠⁠
-1 cup tomatoes -> ⅓ cup tomatoes ⁠⁠
-1 cup asparagus -> ½ cup asparagus⁠⁠
- 2 tsp olive oil -> 3 tsp olive oil⁠⁠
⁠⁠

How to Build a Delicious & Balanced Salad (Swipe to see more salad making ideas). Because salads don’t have to suck!⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
There are an infinite amount of ways to get creative with building a healthy salad! That’s why I thought I’d share some important base ingredients to include in your balanced salads, so you can customize them with all your favorite toppings. ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Of course the most important part of any salad is the base lettuce along with some type of high quality protein and healthy fat. When it comes to lettuce, I suggest going for a darker, leafy green lettuce when you can. Once you’ve decided on your choices, throw in as many of your favorite vegetables as you can find. The more the merrier!  Some of my other favorite salad topping ideas include sliced almonds, fresh fruit, herbs, and healthy grains and legumes.⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Here’s what’s in the Harvest Salad:⁠⁠⁠
-Spinach⁠⁠⁠
-½ cup cooked quinoa ⁠⁠⁠
-½ sweet potato, roasted ⁠⁠⁠
-4-5 cooked beets⁠⁠⁠
-1tbsp goat cheese ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Here’s what’s in the Salmon Walnut:⁠⁠⁠
-Arugula⁠⁠⁠
-Wild-caught salmon ⁠⁠⁠
-¾ cup cherry tomatoes ⁠⁠⁠
-¾ cup cucumber⁠⁠⁠
-2 tbsp walnuts ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Here’s what’s in the Mediterranean:⁠⁠⁠
-Mixed greens⁠⁠⁠
-Grilled chicken breast ⁠⁠⁠
-1 cup bell pepper⁠⁠⁠
-¼ cup red onion ⁠⁠⁠
-Olives ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
Here’s what’s in the Grilled Zucchini:⁠⁠⁠
-Kale ⁠⁠⁠
-2 hard boiled eggs⁠⁠⁠
-¾ cup grilled zucchini ⁠⁠⁠
-½ cup corn ⁠⁠⁠
-½ large avocado ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
What to do:⁠⁠⁠
1- On a bed of lettuce, add your cooked protein, healthy fats, & as many vegetables as you want!⁠⁠⁠
2- Once all your toppings are ready, dig in!⁠⁠⁠
